32. Ad omnestsonoresaeoueurrit. Every candidate foroffiee expected his friends, as a matter of course', to attend him at the election. This attendance was chief among the ‘officia’ or duties of eompliment which friendship enjoined, such as ‘officium togae virilis,’ ‘nuptiarum' and the rest. While the elections were held iu the Campus Martius .the duty of these attendant iriends consisted of three parts: first, they forwarded the candidate's election by recommending him as ‘testes’ or ‘suffragatores;’ seeondly, they voted for him themselves; thirdly, they accompanied him to the Capitol, where some form of inauguration was observed. The third book of Varro, De Re Rust. ia represented as a conversation among the friends of a candidate for the aedileship, who are waiting close by for the result of the election. After the transference of the electione to the Senate, the custom of complimentary attendance on candidates still survived, and at length the ‘suffragatores' became so clamorous as to compel resort to the ballot. Ep. 34.

36. Quinquevieos. Commissions were appointed under this name for various purposes in the time of the republie aud the empire. The number five seems to have been adhered to because found convenient in ease of a division of opinion among the commissionem.
